			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/a-just-weight-is-his-delight/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
<enclosure url="http://traffic.libsyn.com/stewardshipweekly/29.mp3" length="29851230" type="audio/mpeg" />
		<itunes:subtitle>'Let's Be Honest' - A look at doing business in cash, declaring all income to the government &amp; treating others fairly. Today's episode takes us back into the book of Proverbs. Numerous times in the writings of King Solomon we hear warnings against bei...</itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>'Let's Be Honest' - A look at doing business in cash, declaring all income to the government &amp; treating others fairly.
Today's episode takes us back into the book of Proverbs. Numerous times in the writings of King Solomon we hear warnings against being deceitful and cheating people.

Chapter 11 starts off with this powerful verse;
Dishonest scales are an abomination to the Lord, but a just weight is His delight
Then in chapter 13:11 we read a companion verse;
wealth gained by dishonesty will be diminished, but he who gathers by labor will increase
Together, these 2 verses, along with numerous others found in Proverbs, call us to be upright and honourable in how we conduct ourselves in business - and I believe, in our dealings with the government as well.

Although the world economy seems to have improved slightly since the recession of 2008, there is still a fair amount of uncertainty in people’s minds. The housing markets are still shaky, employees are worried about job security and saving for retirement and most households have quite a bit of debt hanging over their heads.

With these unknown variables hanging over our heads, it’s easy to want to look for the short cuts - ways to make and/or hide a few extra bucks. But times have not changed from over 2000 years ago!

When we look at the verses in Proverbs for today’s thoughts, we have teaching from Solomon as to what it is that pleases the Lord. “a just weight is His delight”.
Think about it;
You do nice things that you know will bring a smile to your spouses’ face (flowers, a surprise dinner date, loading the dishwasher without being asked). You also know some of the things that bring delight to your children and your closest friends.

What pleases the Lord? We don't have to guess! Here it is - laid out for us in black &amp; white one of the many things that brings delight to the Lord - a just weight!
What is a dishonest weight?
There is a standard set of weight and measures used in open air market trading (refer to the image above). Small weights would be hidden on the underside of the plate to make the one side heavier in favour of the merchant. The purchaser would have to add more to their side to make things balance.

Although we use currency backed by the governments of our countries, it’s really not so different today and that’s why this proverb is so practical. It’s simply talking about honesty in business and personal transactions.

How great is that! God allows us to please Him in even the little things of life. Anyone, regardless of age, can do what is right when it comes to dealing with other people and money.

What if we’ve already cheated someone? Is it too late? No. Make the effort (humbling and embarrassing as it might be), go back and make it right!

Really? How about I just repent and move on?

And miss bringing joy to God’s heart?!?

No thanks. It’s better to make it right!


Luke 19:1-10 (NIV) - Zacchaeus the Tax Collector



 1 Jesus entered Jericho and was passing through. 2 A man was there by the name of Zacchaeus; he was a chief tax collector and was wealthy. 3 He wanted to see who Jesus was, but because he was short he could not see over the crowd. 4 So he ran ahead and climbed a sycamore-fig tree to see him, since Jesus was coming that way. 5 When Jesus reached the spot, he looked up and said to him, “Zacchaeus, come down immediately. I must stay at your house today.” 6 So he came down at once and welcomed him gladly.

7 All the people saw this and began to mutter, “He has gone to be the guest of a sinner.”

8 But Zacchaeus stood up and said to the Lord, “Look, Lord! Here and now I give half of my possessions to the poor, and if I have cheated anybody out of anything, I will pay back four times the amount.”

9 Jesus said to him, “Today salvation has come to this house, because this man, too, is a son of Abraham. 10 For the Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost.”

