			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p><img class="alignleft" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px;" title="open communication" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/Couple-Talking.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="200" />When it comes to money, <strong>rarely are two people perfectly aligned and on the same page</strong>. The husband may be the spender while the wife is the saver. He thinks 1 bank account will suffice and she thinks having 2 separate accounts may be the route to go. A pile of statements and invoices sits on the corner of the dining room table, and a frustrating (and possibly heated) budget meeting is pending. The lines are being drawn and negotiation strategies are being formed. <strong>Welcome to Married Life Finance &#8211; 101.</strong><br />
&nbsp;</p>
<h3><span style="color: #cca333;"><strong>Who is to blame?</strong></span></h3>
<p><strong></strong>In most situations, no one really. <strong>Probably the biggest struggle for married couples when it comes to money is having different perceptions</strong>.  We each have different upbringings and have had different experiences with money growing up.  My dad passed away when I was only 11 years old and so my mom had the challenge of raising 3 kids on her own with a very limited income.  My wife Elaine on the other hand, was brought up in a home where her dad made good money and was able to take the family of 7 on annual trips that I couldn&#8217;t even dream of as a child.  When we started courting, I was working full time for one of the big Canadian banks and had a great income for my age.  Elaine was still in university and living at home with both a minimal income and only tuition expenses to handle.</p>
<p>When we were married, as with everyone else who says &#8220;I do&#8221; at the front of the church, there was no guarantee that we would immediately begin to think alike in regards to our finances.  <strong>It takes time and openness to understand one another </strong>and learn to appreciate where each other are coming from.  Initially, because of my mom&#8217;s situation, I was extremely tight with the money and pushed hard for us to save up a downpayment on a house and then pay the mortgage off in 10 years.  Now, years later, after having constrained our family to a tight budget, I&#8217;m learning to listen to my wife when she says that the ropes need to be loosened a little.</p>
<p><strong>Am I in the wrong?  Is she in the wrong?</strong> Whenever married couples are facing situations like these where a difference in opinion exists &#8211; it&#8217;s not the time to get frustrated and start making accusations.</p>
<h3><span style="color: #cca333;"><strong>What is the root problem?</strong></span></h3>
<p>Things aren&#8217;t always what they seem.  A spouse who balances the budget down to the last penny each month may be doing so completely out of love for his or her family.  They see their extreme planning as having the foresight to anticipate upcoming expenses and ensure that there is always money available.  While they are scrutinizing each column in the complicated spreadsheet, they believe their actions will be interpreted as an act of service and care by their spouse.  What can (and often does) occur is that their behaviour is perceived as being domineering and controlling.  This misunderstanding permeates through the relationship and can cause hurt feelings and a sense of isolation from one another.  The root problem is not the action itself &#8211; there&#8217;s nothing wrong with what is being done &#8211; the root problem is a breakdown in communication.</p>
<h3><span style="color: #cca333;"><strong>Do we really need to discuss this again?  Honestly?</strong></span></h3>
<p>In a nutshell - <strong>YES</strong>.  Why?  God has some pretty clear wording regarding the relationship between a man and a woman;</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Genesis 2</strong></p>
<p><strong>24. Therefore a man shall leave his father and mother and be joined to his wife, and they shall become one flesh.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>We all know this verse is used in relation to physical intimacy but doesn&#8217;t it include much more than that?  I believe that the scripture makes it quite evident that we are to care for our spouse in the same way that we care for ourselves.  Do we put ourselves in situations where we might be hurt emotionally?  Hopefully not on purpose.  In the same manner then, <strong>we need to be aware of things we might be doing innocently that are hurting our wife or husband</strong>.  If there is tension whenever financial matters are discussed, most likely that&#8217;s an early warning signal that we need to hit the pause button and go back to what we did so well when we first met &#8211; talk.  My wife Elaine is very good at this.</p>
<h3><span style="color: #cca333;"><strong>How do we move forward?</strong></span></h3>
<p>When I&#8217;m oblivious to how she is feeling about our situation &#8211; money or otherwise &#8211; she let&#8217;s me know that it&#8217;s time to talk.  Once the kids are asleep, she sits on our bed and I park myself in the chair with a small cushion behind my back.  After a few minutes, we reluctantly agree that we have totally misinterpreted each others actions and misconstrued what each other said.  We obviously didn&#8217;t set out to <strong>perceive each other incorrectly</strong> - it just happened and needs to be fixed.</p>
<p>From the bit of financial coaching I have done, <strong>I think this simple break-down in communication is one of the biggest challenges facing married couples when it comes to money</strong>.  Instead of thinking and acting independently of one another when managing the money the Lord has put into our possession, married couples need to be joined to one another and become one flesh.</p>
<p>He gives us mouths to speak and ears to hear.  It&#8217;s time to talk.  It&#8217;s time to listen!</p>
