		<item>
		<title>Episode 26 – How to REALLY appreciate what we have</title>
		<link>http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/how-to-really-appreciate-what-we-have/</link>
		<comments>http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/how-to-really-appreciate-what-we-have/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 07 Feb 2012 18:00:48 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>glen@stewardshipweekly.com (Glen Steinson)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Podcast Episodes]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/?p=1271</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Imagine yourself being handed the keys to a brand new car. It’s everything you wanted&#8230; and more. Beautiful design, powerful engine, a great stereo and &#8211; a full tank of gas! After driving it around for a few weeks and getting quite comfortable with it, you have completely forgotten that the owner merely asked you [...]<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
&nbsp;
Subscribe and listen to every new episode via <a href="itpc://feeds.feedburner.com/stewardshipweekly">iTunes</a> (one click subscription)
&nbsp;</p>
]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p>Imagine yourself being handed the keys to a brand new car. It’s everything you wanted&#8230; and more. Beautiful design, powerful engine, a great stereo and &#8211; a full tank of gas! After driving it around for a few weeks and getting quite comfortable with it, you have completely forgotten that <strong>the owner merely asked you to look after it &#8211; to manage it for them while they were away.</strong></p>
<p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1273" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px;" title="Calibre" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/Calibre.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" />When you have to give an account of how you’ve cared for it, it would be completely inappropriate to state “I washed <strong>my</strong> car and had some stripes painted down the side”. It’s not your car! It belongs to the owner &#8211; you are taking care of it. Sure, you get to enjoy it and use it for your benefit, but <strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">your ultimate responsibility is to keep the owner’s best interests in mind</span></strong>. How would they want their car cared for?</p>
<p>This perspective on proper ownership and, understanding the role of a steward is the basis for our appreciation of all that we have.</p>
<p>The Bible states that God owns everything. That includes all that we have and enjoy &#8211; our homes, our vehicles, our money &#8211; everything. <span style="color: #000080;"><strong>When we acknowledge God’s ownership over our lives, the income, and the assets, we learn to have a deep appreciation for what He has entrusted to our care</strong></span>. If we don’t grasp this concept and instead treat things as though they are our own (as in the above example with the car), we quickly take them for granted and don’t appreciate them for long. We fall prey to slick advertising and persistent marketing that focuses our attention on the “bigger, newer, better” mindset.</p>
<blockquote><p>In Exodus 32:7-11, Moses shows us a great example of how we should be thinking;</p>
<p><strong>7 And the LORD said to Moses, &#8220;Go, get down! For <span style="text-decoration: underline; color: #000080;">your</span> people whom you brought out of the land of Egypt have corrupted themselves.</strong></p>
<p><strong>8 &#8220;They have turned aside quickly out of the way which I commanded them. They have made themselves a molded calf, and worshiped it&#8230;&#8217;&#8221;</strong></p>
<p><strong>10 &#8220;Now therefore, let Me alone, that My wrath may burn hot against them and I may consume them. And I will make of you a great nation.&#8221;</strong></p>
<p><strong>11 Then Moses pleaded with the LORD his God, and said: &#8220;LORD, why does Your wrath burn hot against <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><span style="color: #000080;">Your</span></span> people whom You have brought out of the land of Egypt with great power and with a mighty hand?</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>Notice that Moses correctly identifies proper ownership in verse 11 and says to God “they are <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Your</strong></span> people” after they had just been referred to as belonging to Moses in verse 7. He passes the test when he correctly acknowledged God’s rightful place as the Master.</p>
<p>Although the passage is referring to people, I believe we can use it in relation to our money; Here is a man who is leading approximately two million people on a long journey. Anytime an issue arose, they came to him for a decision. Although there were no doubt other men who helped him out, Moses had the final say on every matter. Being in charge, he had to deal with all outcomes of those decisions &#8211; good and bad. It would have been very easy to believe that the ownership belonged to him. In other words &#8211; “<strong>my</strong> people”.</p>
<p>Let’s think for a moment about our income and assets. Just like Moses, any time an issue arises, we make the decisions. Being in charge, we have to deal with all the outcomes of our decisions &#8211; good and bad. It’s easy then to believe that the ownership belongs to us &#8211; “<strong>my</strong> house, <strong>my</strong> business, <strong>my</strong> money”. In every aspect of our finances, we need to acknowledge proper ownership. Everything we have belongs to the Lord. Just like Moses, God has given things into our hands to manage and care for them.</p>
<p><span style="color: #000080;"><strong>Only when we realize that we are ultimately Money Managers for our Master and not for ourselves, do we really appreciate all that we have</strong></span>. To not realize this truth is to entrap ourselves in a cycle where we strive to acquire more and more without fully appreciating who provides for us.<br />
&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p>Find out &#8216;How to REALLY appreciate whatwe have&#8217; &#8211; <a href="http://t.co/0mgcHOmv" title="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/26">stewardshipweekly.com/26</a> &#8211; New Podcast Episode</p>
<p>&mdash; Glen Steinson (@StewardshipWeek) <a href="https://twitter.com/StewardshipWeek/status/167127639281238016" data-datetime="2012-02-08T06:08:28+00:00">February 8, 2012</a></p></blockquote>
