			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-17" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 20px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px;" title="SW 150x150" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/GlenSteinsonD05bR01aP01ZL_150x150pixels.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" />A few weeks ago I was sitting by myself doing a little reading in the book of 2nd Kings. As I made my way from chapter 20 through and into chapter 22, I couldn&#8217;t help but notice <strong>a glaring difference in the way wealth was handled and regarded</strong>. The first person took an unhealthy pride in the amount of wealth that he had amassed and flaunted it excessively. The second person had hired labourers to whom he felt completely comfortable giving wealth to. <span style="color: #a88105;"><strong>The first person saw money as a tool to be used for his own glory. The second person saw money as a tool to be used to glorify God.</strong></span></p>
<h2>Hezekiah &#8211; 15 years to life</h2>
<p>Hezekiah was sick as a dog and his days on earth were numbered. One day, he received a knock at his door and there &#8211; standing in  front of him &#8211; was none other than Isaiah the prophet of God. Instead of bringing a message of hope, the words that fell on his ears sounded like those of an insurance salesman. &#8220;<strong>Set your house in order, for you shall die, and not live</strong>&#8220;. Ouch! After a heartfelt prayer to God, we read that Hezekiah hung his head and wept bitterly.</p>
<p>A few minutes later, Isaiah returned to speak again to Hezekiah who at this point was completely broken. &#8220;<strong>Thus says the Lord&#8230;surely I will heal you&#8230;I will add to your days 15 years</strong>&#8220;.</p>
<p>Some time later, while enjoying the health and physical strength given to him from the Lord, Hezekiah received letters and a present from Mr. Berodach-Baladan, the son of the king of Babylon. <strong>What better way to entertain guests than to show off what you have?</strong> Look, here&#8217;s my vaults full of silver and gold! Check out these lovely spices and precious ointments (maybe there was some frankincense and myrrh in the collection). Do you like my all my treasures? &#8211; <strong><span style="color: #a88105;">Sorry. Wrong focus. These things are temporal and won&#8217;t last.</span></strong></p>
<h2>Josiah&#8217;s Craftsman &#8211; Trustworthy beyond belief</h2>
<p>Now let&#8217;s take a look into the mind and character of young King Josiah. In his few short years as king, he ensured that those around him who held roles of leadership, moral guidance and service for the Lord had exceedingly upright morals. Even the highly skilled craftsmen who were hand selected to complete the work on the temple could be trusted to care for the things of God.</p>
<p>As king, Josiah didn&#8217;t want anything to hamper the progress being made by the carpenters, builders and masons. Instead of having to report to the treasurer and constantly request additional money to purchase more supplies, Josiah thought it best to hand the money directly over to the craftsmen to spend as needed. Absolutely nothing is stated about any one of them individually, but verse 7 gives a glowing report of their characters &#8220;&#8230;<strong>there need be no accounting made with them of the money delivered into their hand, because they deal faithfully</strong>&#8220;. Wow! What an example for us to follow. The bar has been set. The benchmark to which one is measured is high.</p>
<p>Josiah knew that he, nor Hilkiah the high priest, would have to worry that the money was being spent foolishly or carelessly handled. These faithful craftsmen had proven themselves before and now had the distinct honour of caring for God&#8217;s treasury. <strong><span style="color: #a88105;">Correct. Proper focus. Faithful stewards know that eternal rewards for a job well done last forever.</span></strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>Other topics discuss in the episode</h3>
<p>I share that one of the things the kids and I like to do sometimes is watch a YouTube video done by the Prince George High School. It features the song &#8220;Creation Sings&#8221; by Stuart Townend, sung by Steve Green. The video clips that are included are awesome! We like to crank up the volume and sing along with Steve as the kids laugh at the animals bumping into each other and sliding around. To enjoy it, click <strong><span style="color: #a88105;"><a href="http://youtu.be/vXyqg1YKv78" target="_blank"><span style="color: #a88105;">HERE</span></a></span></strong>.</p>
<p>A brand new, hot off the presses book entitled &#8220;the Secret of Generosity&#8221; has been given to me by the author Rob Kuban. Actually, Rob gave me 2 complimentary copies &#8211; one for me to enjoy and another to give away to a lucky listener of the Stewardship Weekly podcast. Rob&#8217;s blog &#8220;Dollars &amp; Doctrine&#8221; has an alliance of which I&#8217;m a member. This upcoming week, I&#8217;ll be speaking with Rob on the phone and will be able to share some of that conversation with you in an upcoming episode. To learn about the alliance, click <strong><span style="color: #a88105;"><a href="http://dollarsanddoctrine.com/2010/12/christian-financial-alliance-bringing-together-sound-biblical-teaching-2/" target="_blank"><span style="color: #a88105;">HERE</span></a></span></strong>.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
