			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p>&nbsp;</p>
<h1><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-867" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 20px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px;" title="Jay Ball" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Jay-Ball-224x300.jpg" alt="" width="224" height="300" />This is Jay.</h1>
<p></p>
<h4><strong>He is a good little monkey and always very curious. Today he is going to be a guest on the Stewardship Weekly podcast and share his story with Glen Steinson, his friend with the yellow hat.</strong></h4>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
For those of you who are familiar with the children&#8217;s books &#8220;Curious George&#8221;, you&#8217;ll know that George goes on all kinds of exciting adventures, makes lots of new friends and learns all kinds of valuable life lessons.  <strong>Jayson Ball is very much alike</strong>.  He has traveled North America extensively, developed a huge network of close friends and been repeatedly encouraged to continue on in his service for Jesus Christ his Lord.</p>
<p>Jay counts it a great priviledge to have been a part of <strong><span style="color: #000080;"><a href="http://teamc3.info/about/" target="_blank"><span style="color: #000080;">Cross Canada Cruisers</span></a></span></strong> and the spread of the gospel from coast to coast. Using 3 classic cars and a unique message of <strong>Ruined, Rescued &amp; Restored</strong>, the team of young Christian men spent the entire summer moving around visiting parks, downtown carnivals and any outdoor celebration where they could find an audience.  Tens of thousands of tracts were handed out and hundreds of conversations were had with curious onlookers who wanted to know about &#8216;the restoration process&#8217;.</p>
<p>From June through August there were a lot of believers who got involved in the outreach. These included the Saints at Sudbury Bible Chapel, New Liskeard Bible Chapel, Forest Bible Chapel, Oakwood Bible Chapel and many more.</p>
<p>In this podcast, <strong>Jay shares his personal testimony with enthusiasm and passion</strong>.  Near the end of the episode, as he shares how others supported him financially when he took a 5 month leave of absence from work, he also shares how he&#8217;s able to periodically do something special for others. The Holy Spirit prompts him to take action and do something that many Christians have never had the opportunity to do. As I was listening to the recorded conversation getting it ready for the podcast, I thought &#8220;what if everyone did that?  Wouldn&#8217;t that be great!?&#8221;  But then a thought hit me &#8211; What if 2 different people, took the same action and yet, because of their completely different situations, only one was acting as a good steward?</p>
<p><span style="color: #000080;">You&#8217;ll see what I&#8217;m referring to as you listen</span>.</p>
<p><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">Pouring Water on the Ground</span></p>
<p>Picture this in your mind &#8212;&gt;  Images of a sever drought. The ground is dried up and cracked open. It&#8217;s unbearably hot and dry with tumbleweeds blowing in the wind. The scorching sun blazes down all day long with not even the smallest cloud in the sky.  It&#8217;s a severe famine with very little food and even less water.  Any water that stills remains is extremely valuable and not a drop is to be wasted. Imagine people lined up by the thousands wherever the precious allotments of supplies are available for distribution.</p>
<p>Now imagine someone who completely ignores the severity of the situation walks right up to the water supply, fills a dozen water pots up to the brim and then proceeds to dump the water out onto a pile of rocks nearby!  As the water disappears into the deep cracks in the ground, the onlookers stare in shock while they can barely swallow because their mouths and throats feel like sand paper! Who on earth would have the audacity to do such a thing?  Is there ever a situation like that where it would be appropriate to act in that manner?</p>
<h3><span style="color: #000080;">Read the story in 1st Kings 17:1-7. Then read all of chapter 18.</span></h3>
<p>Listen to the podcast to hear my thoughts on how 2 people can be in exactly the same circumstances, take exactly the same action and yet yield completely different reactions. Being good stewards does not always mean the same actions done by 2 different people will yield the same results. Pouring the water out onto the ground would be completely cold-hearted and cruel in the visual example I gave you.  Whereas, the same <strong>action taken by Elijah to win the hearts of the Israelites back to God was done in obedience to the Lord&#8217;s command</strong>. The events that unfolded on Mount Carmel with the 450 false prophets of Baal teach us that God is faithful.  He is never changing, steadfast in all His ways and the provider of all that we need, whether it be earthly provisions or rain from the clouds.</p>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
&nbsp;
Subscribe and listen to every new episode via <a href="itpc://feeds.feedburner.com/stewardshipweekly">iTunes</a> (one click subscription)
&nbsp;</p>
