			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><h2><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-17" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px;" title="SW 150x150" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/GlenSteinsonD05bR01aP01ZL_150x150pixels.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" /></h2>
<p>I have two thoughts for today. The first one relates to the idea of <strong>building a name for ourselves</strong>. The other thought was submitted to me just yesterday by a friend as an idea for the show.</p>
<h2>Managing our Talents Wisely</h2>
<p><strong>Acts 9:36-43</strong>. This passage is an account of how Tabitha (also known as Dorcas) was raised from the dead by God through Peter.  As I read this story, there was one verse that really caught my attention.  The author of Acts was lead by the Holy Spirit to finish the account with these words &#8220;<strong>and it became known throughout all Joppa, and many believed on the Lord</strong>&#8220;.</p>
<p>If you had the ability to perform miracles, how quickly would the news spread and the media flock to your doorstep?  Less than 6 hours I&#8217;m sure.  Your instant fame would catapult you to instant stardom.</p>
<p>Although the world at that time didn&#8217;t have any of the technology that we enjoy today, they still found a way to communicate relatively quickly amongst themselves.  Word-of-mouth would fuel excitement within the city and the fastest riders on horseback could then carry the news to adjoining regions within hours.  We cannot overlook the possibility that Peter and the other disciples would have been revered as &#8216;gods&#8217; themselves and given the opportunity to bathe in the spotlight for a season!  Instead, from reading this one closing verse, it&#8217;s evident that <strong>Peter was a wise steward</strong> and ensured that all praise and glory was directed to the rightful owner of the talent he was utilizing.</p>
<h2>Managing our Time Wisely</h2>
<p><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-858" title="hourglass" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/iStock_000003394623XSmall-203x300.jpg" alt="" width="203" height="300" />When you exclude the Lord from your finances, often there never seems to be enough money to cover all the expenses each month.  Yet, time and time again, you hear testimonies of people (like <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/hear-alan-rachel-speak-indonesian/" target="_blank">Alan &amp; Rachel Whatley in episode 16</a>) say that they set aside the first fruits of their income to God and they found that they were able to accomplish more with the remaining 90% than they ever did with the original 100%.  How is that?  I like to say that God uses a different calculator than we do!</p>
<p>My friend <a href="http://kernelsofwheat.com" target="_blank">Jim Kerwin</a> says that <strong>the same concept holds true with our prayer life</strong>.  Time spent in quiet, reflective and non-rushed prayer is <span style="text-decoration: underline;">always</span> beneficial.  It&#8217;s <span style="text-decoration: underline;">always</span> a good use of our time.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote><p><span style="color: #c2a23d;"><strong>By God&#8217;s great power, the following math equations hold true;</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="color: #c2a23d;"><strong>24 hours subtract time spent in prayer &gt; 24 hours</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="color: #c2a23d;"><strong>More time praying = More time to do things</strong></span></p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Martin Luther is reported to have said, &#8220;I pray two hours every day; and days that I know will be very busy, I pray three hours.&#8221;</p>
<p>It&#8217;s time to consider <strong>tithing your time</strong>.  To this world, it doesn&#8217;t even come close to making sense.  That&#8217;s OK.  Just like Peter, we&#8217;re not living for this world.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: 13px;"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><strong>&#8212;-&gt; P.S.</strong></span> &#8211; This is the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">first</span> episode I&#8217;ve released with <span style="text-decoration: underline;">no editing</span>.  It might not be as polished as some of the others but it&#8217;s genuine!</span></p>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
&nbsp;
Subscribe and listen to every new episode via <a href="itpc://feeds.feedburner.com/stewardshipweekly">iTunes</a> (one click subscription)
&nbsp;</p>
