			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><h2>An Interview with Scott Thomson &#8211; Serving the Lord through Stewardship</h2>
<p>This new episode is substantially longer than previous ones. In it, I had the great privilege to interview a new friend that was introduced to me by <strong><a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/upcoming-interview-with-kaz-ortiz/" target="_blank">Kaz Ortiz</a></strong> who you&#8217;ll remember from <a title="Episode 4" href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/4/" target="_blank">episode 4</a>. I was introduced to <strong>Scott Thomson</strong> when our family was down at Greenwood Hills Pennsylvania this summer. Scott, who was heavily influenced by his dad at a young age when he was taught <strong>solid teaching on biblical finance</strong>, lives in York, Pennsylvania.</p>
<p>He holds a <strong>Masters Degree in Corporate Finance</strong> and has recently become a <strong>Certified Financial Planner (CFP)</strong>.   For many years now, both as his passion and occupation, Scott advises Christians on how to be good stewards. He works with a group called <strong><a title="Believers Stewardship Services" href="http://www.believerstewardship.org" target="_blank">Believers Stewardship Services</a></strong> who encourages believers to follow biblical principles in alignment with US tax laws and regulations.</p>
<p>He draws to our attention that there is teaching about money in almost every book of the bible &#8211; from Genesis to Revelation. He references Abraham&#8217;s wealth and the role it played in his life. He also points out that Job&#8217;s wealth (and sudden removal of it) hold many valuable truths for us to glean. Then in the New Testament, our attention is drawn to the time when a poor, lame man approached Peter and John asking for money. Instead of handing the man some coins, Peter and John are able to offer something far better.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-592" title="Scott &amp; Glen" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Scott-Glen-300x223.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="223" /></p>
<p>Our conversation then turned to <strong>estate planning</strong>. Scott advises that this is something that all adult Christians should seriously think about. You want to have a proper will in place for asset distribution in accordance with your Christian beliefs. Should you pass away before the Lord returns, and you don&#8217;t have a will, it&#8217;s highly unlikely that the government will choose to distribute some of the funds to the Lords work.</p>
<p>I then mention this great little reference book - <a href="http://www.christianbook.com/what-the-bible-says-about-money/9781597899925/pd/899925?item_code=WW&amp;netp_id=503299&amp;event=ESRCG&amp;view=details" target="_blank">What the Bible says about money</a>.</p>
<p>There is another organization that Scott has been heavily involved with over the years named <strong><a title="Christian Missions in Many Lands" href="http://www.cmml.us/" target="_blank">Christian Missions in Many Lands</a> (CMML)</strong>.  His time with both Believers Stewardship Services and CMML  has corresponded nicely with one another allowing him to be a blessing to many, many people over the years.</p>
<p>Scott shares with passion how his dad taught him some valuable truths about finance. Using a simple calculator and the traditional numeric tables, he learned all about compound interest and the time value of money. It was explained to him that this can be a very powerful force when working for you, but can be an even more powerful force when working against you. <strong>Avoidance of debt was stressed and the freedom associated with working hard and living on less than you make</strong>.</p>
<p>One of the consequences of having outstanding debt as a believer in Jesus Christ, is that if you feel led to serve the Lord outside of your income earning occupation,  your intentions will be hampered by your repayment obligations. <strong>It&#8217;s hard to serve, tithe and give generously when our allegiances are to the financial institutions.</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
&nbsp;
Subscribe and listen to every new episode via <a href="itpc://feeds.feedburner.com/stewardshipweekly">iTunes</a> (one click subscription)
&nbsp;</p>
