<enclosure url="http://traffic.libsyn.com/stewardshipweekly/12.mp3" length="53644457" type="audio/mpeg" />
		<itunes:subtitle>An Interview with Scott Thomson - Serving the Lord through Stewardship This new episode is substantially longer than previous ones. In it, I had the great privilege to interview a new friend that was introduced to me by Kaz Ortiz who you'll remember f...</itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>An Interview with Scott Thomson - Serving the Lord through Stewardship
This new episode is substantially longer than previous ones. In it, I had the great privilege to interview a new friend that was introduced to me by Kaz Ortiz who you'll remember from episode 4. I was introduced to Scott Thomson when our family was down at Greenwood Hills Pennsylvania this summer. Scott, who was heavily influenced by his dad at a young age when he was taught solid teaching on biblical finance, lives in York, Pennsylvania.

He holds a Masters Degree in Corporate Finance and has recently become a Certified Financial Planner (CFP).   For many years now, both as his passion and occupation, Scott advises Christians on how to be good stewards. He works with a group called Believers Stewardship Services who encourages believers to follow biblical principles in alignment with US tax laws and regulations.

He draws to our attention that there is teaching about money in almost every book of the bible - from Genesis to Revelation. He references Abraham's wealth and the role it played in his life. He also points out that Job's wealth (and sudden removal of it) hold many valuable truths for us to glean. Then in the New Testament, our attention is drawn to the time when a poor, lame man approached Peter and John asking for money. Instead of handing the man some coins, Peter and John are able to offer something far better.

Our conversation then turned to estate planning. Scott advises that this is something that all adult Christians should seriously think about. You want to have a proper will in place for asset distribution in accordance with your Christian beliefs. Should you pass away before the Lord returns, and you don't have a will, it's highly unlikely that the government will choose to distribute some of the funds to the Lords work.

I then mention this great little reference book - What the Bible says about money.

There is another organization that Scott has been heavily involved with over the years named Christian Missions in Many Lands (CMML).  His time with both Believers Stewardship Services and CMML  has corresponded nicely with one another allowing him to be a blessing to many, many people over the years.

Scott shares with passion how his dad taught him some valuable truths about finance. Using a simple calculator and the traditional numeric tables, he learned all about compound interest and the time value of money. It was explained to him that this can be a very powerful force when working for you, but can be an even more powerful force when working against you. Avoidance of debt was stressed and the freedom associated with working hard and living on less than you make.

One of the consequences of having outstanding debt as a believer in Jesus Christ, is that if you feel led to serve the Lord outside of your income earning occupation,  your intentions will be hampered by your repayment obligations. It's hard to serve, tithe and give generously when our allegiances are to the financial institutions.

 </itunes:summary>
