			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Interview with Ismail Nemr &#8211; Part 2 of 2</h2>
<p>One of the opening thoughts in this episode focuses on contentment. Do people get contentment from money? How about from physical possessions?</p>
<p>To get us started this week, Ismail makes a startling statement. “If sin was never introduced, <strong>we would never have had the need for money</strong> because we would still have been in perfect harmony with God and with one another and therefore had no need to buy and sell.”</p>
<p>One of the bitter consequences of sin is <strong>selfishness</strong>. Men and women live for themselves trying to quench the thirst in their souls. The book of Ecclesiastes, in chapter 2, reminds us that these pursuits are all in vain. One can only derive <strong><span style="color: #cca333;">true fulfillment through the Lord Jesus Christ</span></strong>. We came into this world with nothing and will likewise leave with the same.</p>
<p>Once you listen to this episode you&#8217;ll agree with Ismail and myself that the Lord himself chose 2nd Corinthians 8:9 to be a key verse for our thoughts today. Unknown to each other before we recorded this interview, the words of this verse were on both our minds.  <em><strong>For you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that though He was rich, yet for your sakes He became poor, that you through His poverty might become rich</strong>.</em></p>
<p>As many of us do when discussing the topic, Ismail quoted the verse &#8211; <em>The love of money is the root of all evil</em>.  He stresses that money itself is not evil but that money is &#8220;a blessing from the hands of our loving Father and we should be sure to use it for His honor and glory”.  What is the object of our hearts? Money or Christ?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
&nbsp;
Subscribe and listen to every new episode via <a href="itpc://feeds.feedburner.com/stewardshipweekly">iTunes</a> (one click subscription)
&nbsp;</p>
