			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>An Interview with Ismail Nemr &#8211; Part 1 of 2</h2>
<p>In this episode, I had the great privilege of being able to interview a dear friend of mine named Ismail Nemr.   This brother in the Lord lives in Detroit Michigan after having <strong>moved to the United States from Lebanon</strong>.   Unlike most of us, his fellow countryman back home hates him.   Having come from a Shiite Muslim background, his conversion to Christianity has made him a target whenever he returns to visit family.</p>
<p>Our interview starts out with Ismail telling a story of plans he had back in 2006 for a gospel outreach in the greater Detroit area. He shares how he had a vision for a <strong>3 night gospel outreach to the Arabic community</strong>. After tallying the expected costs to rent a facility, provide meals and cover miscellaneous expenses, it was determined that approximately $20,000 would be needed. Not sure where the money would come from, Ismail and the committee that had formed to oversee the event proceeded in faith. Appropriately named “<strong>The Great Physician Conference</strong>”, this outreach is going into its 7th year. Ismail shares with us that, in the 1st year of the conference, 100 people in attendance repented and surrendered their life to Christ.</p>
<p><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-546" style="margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px;" title="Ismail Nemr" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Ismail-Nemr-236x300.jpg" alt="" width="236" height="300" /></p>
<p>The 2nd story that he shares in the podcast is how he was off work for 8 months in 2008. Lying in bed for <strong>21 days in excruciating pain</strong> and looking at a possible surgery &#8211; he wasn&#8217;t worried about their finances. His employer at the time reassured him that his paycheck would continue to arrive in the mail as usual. However, things do not always go as planned. Promises made with good intentions are not always honored. Listen as <strong><span style="color: #cca333;">Ismail draws parallels between what happens in our lives and a ship being tossed to and fro in a violent storm</span></strong>. It&#8217;s obvious from his testimony that Ismail has read Matthew 6:25-34. “Therefore do not worry, saying, &#8216;what shall we eat?&#8217; or &#8216;what shall we drink?&#8217; or &#8216;what shall we wear?&#8217;&#8230; for your Heavenly Father knows that you need all these things.&#8221;</p>
<p>The interview finishes with Ismail sharing how he and his family are now in a time of transition.  It appears that the Lord is calling him into full-time ministry and that his time working for his current employer may soon be drawing to a close. He shares with the listening audience how <strong>it&#8217;s his desire to fully utilize the spiritual gifts entrusted to him by God</strong>.</p>
<p>This dear brother  reminds us that “the Lord gives grace and he renews the energy&#8221;. Next week in episode 11, we will enjoy the 2nd half of the telephone interview as Ismail continues and shares some thoughts he has on money and stewardship.  You definitely want to ensure that you&#8217;re subscribed to the podcast so you don&#8217;t miss his powerful and motivating message.</p>
<p>If after listening to this episode you would like to leave some feedback for Ismail, please call the Listener Toll-Free Hotline and leave a voicemail for him.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
