			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><h3></h3>
<p>When trying to be good stewards for the Lord, it sure is nice to get some encouragement along the way.</p>
<p>This episode looks at a select few individuals who have gone out of their way to be an encourager to someone else.</p>
<h3></h3>
<h3>Podcast Outline;</h3>
<h2>Onesiphorus</h2>
<p>To start this episode we refer to <strong>2 Timothy 1:16-17</strong> and look at a man who Paul said &#8220;often refreshed him&#8221;.  Instead of sitting around and discussing Paul&#8217;s imprisonment with the other believers, he journeyed to Rome and managed to track down the military compound and very cell that his friend was sitting in.  Knowing the state that Paul was in, Onesiphorus utilized his time well and &#8220;zealously&#8221; sought out a friend who desperately needed encouragement.</p>
<p>It was a message spoken by my brother-in-law, <strong>Brian Cretney</strong>, that first drew my attention to Onesiphorus.  Although I had read that passage numerous times before, I had completely glossed over those two short verses that define his true character.</p>
<h2>Leslie Samuel</h2>
<p>Through his podcast at <a href="http://www.learningwithleslie.com" target="_blank">Learning with Leslie</a>, this new friend of mine in the Lord is helping me be a better steward of my time and internet resources by teaching me how to enhance this web site.  After I left a message for Leslie on his voice mail, he talked about Stewardship Weekly on his podcast and suggested that his listeners check it out for themselves!  I discuss how much that meant to me and then included a clip from his show for you to hear.</p>
<h2>Philemon</h2>
<p>Although the shortest of all Paul&#8217;s letters preserved for us in the Bible, his brief correspondence to Philemon reveals a remarkable man.  Because of Philemon&#8217;s well known reputation as one who &#8216;refreshed the hearts of the Saints&#8217;, Paul was confident and bold enough to request pardon for run-away salve <strong>Onesimus</strong> who had recently accepted Christ.  It seems likely from our insight into his character, that Philemon was a good steward of all that was in his household &#8211; including his slaves.  Paul asks him to accept Onesimus back, not as a slave, but as a &#8220;beloved brother&#8221;.</p>
<p>I think it&#8217;s safe to assume that Paul&#8217;s intervention on his behalf was a great encouragement to Onesimus.</p>
<h2>Guest Feedback</h2>
<p>Whenever you listen to an episode that features a guest sharing their stewardship testimony or teaching on financial biblical truths, please <strong>call the toll-free voice-mail feedback line at 1-888-546-0325</strong>. Leave a message of appreciation and encouragement for the guest and I&#8217;ll be sure that it&#8217;s forwarded to them after four weeks (along with all other feedback received).</p>
<h2><strong>In Closing&#8230;</strong></h2>
<p>What can you do this week to be an encouragement to someone?  Send an e-mail? Work along side of them on a project?  Anonymously give some money to a friend in need?</p>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
&nbsp;
Subscribe and listen to every new episode via <a href="itpc://feeds.feedburner.com/stewardshipweekly">iTunes</a> (one click subscription)
&nbsp;</p>
