			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><h3><strong>Hi everyone, welcome back!</strong></h3>
<p>This week&#8217;s episode of Stewardship Weekly is going to be a little different.  Usually I take the first half of the show to share my thoughts on a passage of scripture or a concept relating to biblical finance.  Then after 15 minutes or so, the second half is either a success story or a guest message.</p>
<p>This week however, the plans have changed.  <strong>The entire episode is an interview I just had with a friend of mine named Peter Zein</strong>.  My original intent was to edit the recording and bring it down to 20 mins or so, but, one of the reasons I&#8217;m hosting the Stewardship Weekly podcast is to have the show be an encouragement to the listening audience.  After going over the content numerous times, I decided that it would be in your best interest to hear almost the entire conversation.  Once you hear it, I&#8217;m sure you&#8217;ll agree.</p>
<h3><strong>About Our Guest</strong></h3>
<p>Peter Zein is a man who <span style="color: #c19b00;"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">will never achieve financial independence</span></strong></span>.  It&#8217;s not because he makes foolish money decisions.  It&#8217;s not because he lacks the knowledge required for long term planning.  Quite the opposite.  He&#8217;ll never achieve financial independence &#8211; because <strong>he doesn&#8217;t want to</strong>.  If financial independence is reaching the point in your life where you feel safe and secure with what you have and no longer have to trust in anyone else &#8211; he doesn&#8217;t want it.</p>
<p>Peter has placed his trust in God alone to provide for his every need &#8211; financial and otherwise.  Through obedience and sacrifice, he has yielded his will to that of his Heavenly Father and, over many years, has never been disappointed.</p>
<p>The podcast is a 35 minute personal testimony of a man who has faced many challenges and adversities in his life.  It reveals a loyal steward who has been a faithful servant &#8211; and is an example for all of us.</p>
<address><strong><br />
</strong></address>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
