]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p>Have you ever had to make a difficult decision concerning a major purchase?  Of course you have.  Who hasn&#8217;t?</p>
<p>In this episode, we spend some time together <strong>looking at the start of Gideon&#8217;s public life</strong> as he gets ready to lead the nation of Israel.  As we well know, he was quite unsure of himself and used the &#8220;<strong>fleece test</strong>&#8221; to learn the mind of God.</p>
<p>Do we do the same?  Is there merit to asking for a sign from above when faced with big decisions?</p>
<p><span style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">Show Contents -</span></p>
<ul>
<li>Gideon is called by God.</li>
<li>Israel is again at a low point in their history and have turned their backs on God.  They are living in complete disobedience and are doing evil in the sight of the Lord.</li>
<li>The Lord has delivered them into the hand of the Midianites for 7 years.</li>
<li>Judges 6:2-5</li>
<li>We see Gideon working hard to provide for his family during difficult circumstances.</li>
<li>Judges 6:6, 12-13</li>
<li>Gideon did not have a clear picture of the way things really were.  He thinks that God has forsaken them!</li>
<li>It wasn’t God that had forsaken them, it was the nation of Israel that had forsaken God!</li>
<li>What happens when we slack off and take our relationship with the Lord for granted?</li>
<li>Judges 6:14-16</li>
<li>Gideon is looking at himself and doubting his ability to carry out the Lord’s plans.  And you know what?  He should!</li>
<li>But he wasn’t going to be alone!  God said “Have I not sent you?”  &amp; “surely I will be with you”.</li>
<li>Gideon was thinking ahead to the challenges that would await him and was unsure of things.</li>
<li><strong>What about when we have a genuine need and are truly unsure what the Lord would have us to do?  Is it OK to put out a fleece like Gideon did and ask God for a sign?</strong></li>
<li>Judges 6:36-40</li>
<li>Instead of ignoring the Lord and returning to his routine of secretly threshing wheat at the winepresses, he asks for clarification &#8211; a sign.</li>
<li>Why not do as Gideon did and ask for a sign?  <strong>Give God a chance to clarify things.</strong></li>
<li>Nowadays, with quick and accessible credit, the world has made it extremely easy to skip these opportunities for the Lord to show us a sign.</li>
<li>Gideon had to sleep on it.  His answers from the Lord didn’t come until the next morning.</li>
<li><span style="color: #7f4e19;"><strong><span style="font-family: Georgia; font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">Interview with Kaz &amp; Rosie Ortiz &#8211; We serve a Great God!</span></span></strong></span></li>
</ul>
<p><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-452" title="Kaz &amp; Rosie Ortiz" src="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Kaz-Rosie-Ortiz-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Be sure to visit the web site at <a href="http://www.stewardshipweekly.com">Stewardship Weekly</a>
