<enclosure url="http://traffic.libsyn.com/stewardshipweekly/4.mp3" length="30128337" type="audio/mpeg" />
		<itunes:subtitle>Have you ever had to make a difficult decision concerning a major purchase?  Of course you have.  Who hasn't? - In this episode, we spend some time together looking at the start of Gideon's public life as he gets ready to lead the nation of Israel.</itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>Have you ever had to make a difficult decision concerning a major purchase?  Of course you have.  Who hasn't?

In this episode, we spend some time together looking at the start of Gideon's public life as he gets ready to lead the nation of Israel.  As we well know, he was quite unsure of himself and used the "fleece test" to learn the mind of God.

Do we do the same?  Is there merit to asking for a sign from above when faced with big decisions?

Show Contents -

	Gideon is called by God.
	Israel is again at a low point in their history and have turned their backs on God.  They are living in complete disobedience and are doing evil in the sight of the Lord.
	The Lord has delivered them into the hand of the Midianites for 7 years.
	Judges 6:2-5
	We see Gideon working hard to provide for his family during difficult circumstances.
	Judges 6:6, 12-13
	Gideon did not have a clear picture of the way things really were.  He thinks that God has forsaken them!
	It wasn’t God that had forsaken them, it was the nation of Israel that had forsaken God!
	What happens when we slack off and take our relationship with the Lord for granted?
	Judges 6:14-16
	Gideon is looking at himself and doubting his ability to carry out the Lord’s plans.  And you know what?  He should!
	But he wasn’t going to be alone!  God said “Have I not sent you?”  &amp; “surely I will be with you”.
	Gideon was thinking ahead to the challenges that would await him and was unsure of things.
	What about when we have a genuine need and are truly unsure what the Lord would have us to do?  Is it OK to put out a fleece like Gideon did and ask God for a sign?
	Judges 6:36-40
	Instead of ignoring the Lord and returning to his routine of secretly threshing wheat at the winepresses, he asks for clarification - a sign.
	Why not do as Gideon did and ask for a sign?  Give God a chance to clarify things.
	Nowadays, with quick and accessible credit, the world has made it extremely easy to skip these opportunities for the Lord to show us a sign.
	Gideon had to sleep on it.  His answers from the Lord didn’t come until the next morning.
	Interview with Kaz &amp; Rosie Ortiz - We serve a Great God!



